[[File:Nakayama Chausuyama Kofun, haisho.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|{{ill|Haisho|ja|拝所|lt=Worship site|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haisho|qq=}} for Ōkibitsuhiko no Mikoto's tomb}}]]

'''Nakayama Chausuyama Kofun''' (中山茶臼山古墳) is a {{ill|Kofun|en|Kofun|WD=Q1141225|lt=Kofun|1=Kofun}} located in {{ill|北區|en|北區|WD=Q1180096|lt=Kita-ku (Okayama)|1=北區}}, {{ill|Okayama|en|Okayama|WD=Q200078|lt=Okayama|1=Okayama}}, {{ill|Okayama Prefecture|en|Okayama Prefecture|WD=Q132936|lt=Okayama Prefecture|1=Okayama Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|Zenpō-kōen-fun|en|Zenpō-kōen-fun|WD=Q11268718|lt=Zenpō-kōen-fun|1=Zenpō-kōen-fun}} (keyhole-shaped tumulus).

The actual person buried here is unknown, but the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|en|Imperial Household Agency|WD=Q1143602|lt=Imperial Household Agency|1=Imperial Household Agency}} has Historic Site1 the mound as the tomb of {{ill|Kibitsuhiko-no-mikoto|lt=Ōkibitsuhiko no Mikoto|ja|大吉備津彦命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kibitsuhiko-no-mikoto|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 吉備津彦命}}, a son of Emperor Kōrei, the 7th emperor of Japan.

== Overview ==

Nakayama Chausuyama Kofun is a large keyhole-shaped tumulus built on the summit of the independent hill range known as "Kibi no Nakayama" to the west of Okayama City. The mound is exceptionally well-preserved to this day.{{Sfn|Shoryobu Journal, Mausoleum Section Vol. 61|2010|pp=21-29}} It is managed by the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|en|Imperial Household Agency|WD=Q1143602|lt=Imperial Household Agency|1=Imperial Household Agency}}, which conducted a mound measurement survey in 2008.{{Sfn|Shoryobu Journal, Mausoleum Section Vol. 61|2010|pp=21-29}}

The tumulus features a "paddle-shaped" keyhole design, with the front rectangular section facing south.{{Sfn|Shoryobu Journal, Mausoleum Section Vol. 61|2010|pp=21-29}} The mound is constructed in two tiers.{{Sfn|Shoryobu Journal, Mausoleum Section Vol. 61|2010|pp=21-29}} Surface features include paving stones and evidence suggesting the presence of a haniwa (clay figurine) row based on haniwa fragments.{{Sfn|Shoryobu Journal, Mausoleum Section Vol. 61|2010|pp=21-29}} However, further details remain unclear.

The mound is estimated to have been built during the early Kofun period, though precise dating remains uncertain due to limited evidence.<ref name="Okayama City">[http://www.city.okayama.jp/museum/kofun1/09.html Nakayama Chausuyama Kofun] (Okayama City Museum "Explore Okayama's Historic Site").</ref> Its location combines coastal views of Kibitsu and inland plains, suggesting both maritime and inland significance.{{Sfn|Nakayama Chausuyama Kofun (Heibonsha)|1988}}{{Sfn|Shoryobu Journal, Mausoleum Section Vol. 61|2010|pp=21-29}} The tumulus is situated on the historical boundary between Bizen and Bitchū Provinces. Other nearby tumuli in Kibi no Nakayama include early-period tumuli such as {{ill|Yatōjiyama Kofun|lt=Yatōjiyama Kofun|lt=Yatōji Yama Kofun|ja|矢藤治山古墳|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yatōji Yama Kofun|qq=}} and mid-period tumuli such as {{ill|Onoe Kurumayama Kofun|en|Onoe Kurumayama Kofun|WD=Q28685132|lt=Onoe Kurumayama Kofun|1=Onoe Kurumayama Kofun}} (a Historic Site1 national historic site).

== Historical Record ==

* 1874 (Meiji 7): Designated as the tomb of Ōkibitsuhiko no Mikoto.{{Sfn|Shoryobu Journal, Mausoleum Section Vol. 61|2010|pp=21-29}}
* 1980 (Shōwa 55): Excavation monitoring during torii reconstruction; Yayoi pottery discovered.{{Sfn|Shoryobu Journal, Mausoleum Section Vol. 61|2010|pp=21-29}}
* 2008: Mound measurement survey conducted by the Imperial Household Agency.{{Sfn|Shoryobu Journal, Mausoleum Section Vol. 61|2010|pp=21-29}}

== Mound area ==

[[File:Nakayama Chausuyama Kofun, kouenbu.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Rear mound of the tumulus}}{{small|Foreground: An Observation Kannon shrine at Hattoku-ji Okuin, speculated to be a typeer {{ill|Iwakura rock|en|Iwakura rock|WD=Q11587880|lt=Iwakura (Shinto)|1=Iwakura rock}}.}}]]

The mound's area, based on Imperial Household Agency measurements, are as follows:{{Sfn|Shoryobu Journal, Mausoleum Section Vol. 61|2010|pp=21-29}}

* Mound length: 105 m
* Rear circular section: Elliptical (axes misaligned with the main axis of the mound). Two tiers.
** Diameter: Long axis 68 m, short axis 64 m
** Height: 11 m
* Front rectangular section: Two tiers.
** Length: 63 m
** Width: Approximately 45 m
** Height: 5 m
* Constriction section:
** Width: Approximately 23 m

Earlier measurements estimated a mound length of approximately 120 m, but the 2008 survey revised this to the above area.{{Sfn|Shoryobu Journal, Mausoleum Section Vol. 61|2010|pp=21-29}} The mound's design is considered to mirror half the proportional size of the {{ill|Andon'yama Kofun|ja|行燈山古墳|1=Andon-yama Kofun|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Andon'yama Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Andon-yama Kofun|qq=}} in Nara Prefecture.{{Sfn|Nakayama Chausuyama Kofun (Heibonsha)|1988}}

== Buried Person ==

The actual buried individual remains unknown. However, the Imperial Household Agency designates the mound as the tomb of Ōkibitsuhiko no Mikoto, a son of Emperor Kōrei.<ref>Imperial Ministry's Bureau of Mausolea [{{NDLDC|1237123/8}} 'Ryo Bo Yōran'] (1934, {{ill|National Diet Library|en|National Diet Library|WD=Q477675|lt=National Diet Library|1=National Diet Library}} Digital Collection).</ref><ref>'Mausoleum Topography Collection, Compact Edition,' Imperial Household Agency's Bureau of Mausolea, Gakuseisha, 2014, p. 400.</ref> Historical texts, including the {{ill|Kojiki|en|Kojiki|WD=Q813031|lt=Kojiki|1=Kojiki}} and {{ill|Nihon Shoki|en|Nihon Shoki|WD=Q813935|lt=Nihon Shoki|1=Nihon Shoki}}, reference Ōkibitsuhiko no Mikoto as a conqueror of Kibi Province and a participant in the {{ill|Shido Shogun|ja|四道将軍|1=Shidō Shōgun|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shido Shogun|13=User:Immanuelle/Shidō Shōgun|qq=}} campaign.{{Sfn|Ōkibitsuhiko no Mikoto (Kokushi)|}}{{Sfn|Hikoisaseri (Ancient Clans)|2010}}

